  <div class="section-label">Model methodology</div>
  <div class="method-grid" style="margin-bottom:60px;">
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="mc-label">Scarcity — 25%</div>
      <div class="mc-weight">PSA 9 population</div>
      <div class="mc-desc">How many PSA 9 copies exist. Lower pop = higher score. PSA 10 scarcity as bonus signal. The rarest cards in high grade command the best premiums over time.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="mc-label">Entry cost — 20%</div>
      <div class="mc-weight">Raw + grading cost</div>
      <div class="mc-desc">All-in cost to acquire a raw copy and submit to PSA. Lower cost = more cards you can acquire and diversify. Estimated at 12% of TCGplayer low + $50 grading.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="mc-label">Momentum — 20%</div>
      <div class="mc-weight">Set + price trend</div>
      <div class="mc-desc">Set-level momentum (where is collector interest heading) combined with Cardmarket 7-day vs 30-day price trend. Buying early into a trend is the edge.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="mc-label">Grade premium — 15%</div>
      <div class="mc-weight">PSA 9 → 10 delta</div>
      <div class="mc-desc">The upside if a submitted raw comes back PSA 10. Cards with very few PSA 10s have massive premiums. Finding a gem mint raw in an under-graded set is the highest alpha play.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="mc-label">Value / ROI — 10%</div>
      <div class="mc-weight">Return on investment</div>
      <div class="mc-desc">Expected return if the card grades PSA 9: (PSA 9 market − all-in cost) / all-in cost. Pure economics — how much upside relative to what you spend.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="mc-label">Liquidity — 10%</div>
      <div class="mc-weight">Total graded population</div>
      <div class="mc-desc">Higher total graded = more buyers in the market = faster you can sell when you want to. A scarce card that nobody trades is a problem. Liquidity matters.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

